# Statistical Inference: Simulation and Maximum Likelihood Estimation

## Overview

This project applies statistical inference techniques to both simulated and real-world datasets. It focuses on evaluating estimator performance using Monte Carlo simulation and building a logistic regression model using maximum likelihood estimation (MLE).

The project demonstrates how statistical methods can be used to handle skewed data, assess robustness to outliers, and extract meaningful insights from real-world datasets related to global health.

---

## Why This Project Matters

In real-world data science, datasets are often noisy, skewed, and affected by outliers. This project highlights:

- The importance of choosing appropriate estimators
- The impact of data contamination on statistical conclusions
- How MLE is used to build interpretable predictive models
- How statistical analysis can inform real-world policy (UNSDG Goal 3)

---

## Technologies Used

- R
- Quarto
- dplyr, ggplot2
- gapminder dataset
- Statistical techniques:
  - Monte Carlo simulation
  - Robust estimation
  - Maximum Likelihood Estimation (MLE)
  - Logistic regression
  - Fisher Information
  - Confidence intervals
  - Profile likelihood

